  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening Older persons Support in Humanitarian Action (SOSHA) after cyclone IDAI</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Aim of the project is to improve the resilience of older persons and people living with disabilities in Chimanimani and Chipinge districts. This project is a continuation of the successful pilot phase whose main objective was to provide immediate psycho-social relief as well as build critical information base for a recovery phase. The pilot phase &#x201C;Strengthening Older Persons Support in Humanitarian Action (SOSHA)&#x201D; was implemented in Chipinge and Chimanimani districts of Manicaland Province. It sought to enhance older person&apos;s access to and participation in emergence relief through building a solid information base on their needs and aspirations. Older Citizen Monitoring (OCM), a concept that is designed to mobilise older persons and build their capacity to gather necessary evidence for grassroots advocacy, mobilise themselves to speak with a unified voice and enhance their self-organising skills was introduced in the two districts. OCM groups were set up in each village. These village based OCM groups were supervised by Older Persons Committees that were set at ward level.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Outcome 1: Improved psycho-social wellbeing of Older Persons and people with disabilities</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Outcome 2: Improved access to health services by older persons and people with disabilities</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Outcome 3: Strengthened needs information sharing and collaboration with development agencies working in the target areas for easy referrals</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Outcome 4: Inclusion of Older Persons issues in Disaster Risk Reduction in Older Persons policy</narrative>
  </description>
